		<item>
		<title>How COVID-19 transformed Pokémon Go into “Pokémon stay-at-home”</title>
		<link>https://arstechnica.com/?p=1691269</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 13 Jul 2020 17:54:49 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Ars Staff]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Gaming & Culture]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://arstechnica.com/?p=1691269</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Players worry how remote play will affect a game centered on social encounters.]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id="rss-wrap">
<figure class="intro-image intro-left"><img src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/pokemon-go-masks-800x450.jpg" alt="Gotta catch 'em all while not catching coronavirus (TM)."><p class="caption" style="font-size:0.8em"><a href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/pokemon-go-masks.jpg" class="enlarge-link" data-height="563" data-width="1000">Enlarge</a> <span class="sep">/</span> Gotta catch 'em all while not catching coronavirus (TM). (credit: Niantic / Aurich Lawson)</p>  </figure><div><a name="page-1"></a></div>
<p>Since its launch in 2016, the premise of mobile titan <i>Pokémon Go</i> has centered on roaming the outdoors in search of mystical little creatures. As a result, it’s a game that’s particularly ill-suited to pandemic-derived restrictions on movement.</p>
<p>In an attempt to remedy this, <i>Pokémon Go</i> developer Niantic has <a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2020/03/amid-pandemic-pokemon-go-updates-make-it-easier-to-play-from-home/">rolled out</a> regular <a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2020/03/pokemon-go-adjusts-to-the-quarantine-era/">updates</a> to make the game more quarantine-compatible in recent months. This has led to a new era of play among many in the <i>Pokémon Go</i> scene. Call it “stay-at-home, play-at-home.”</p>
<p>Such a systemic change in the way <i>Pokémon Go</i> is played was likely necessary for the game to survive in an era where many (if not most) players were unable or afraid to travel and gather together for their usual raids. By providing players with a way to play from home, Niantic is effectively removing the golden geese taunting them from the park across the road.</p></div><p><a href="https://arstechnica.com/?p=1691269#p3">Read 24 remaining paragraphs</a> | <a href="https://arstechnica.com/?p=1691269&comments=1">Comments</a></p><div class="feedflare">
<a href="http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/index?a=9lr_bsyKZCQ:cSMDwISYc2A:V_sGLiPBpWU"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/index?i=9lr_bsyKZCQ:cSMDwISYc2A:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/index?a=9lr_bsyKZCQ:cSMDwISYc2A:F7zBnMyn0Lo"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/index?i=9lr_bsyKZCQ:cSMDwISYc2A:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/index?a=9lr_bsyKZCQ:cSMDwISYc2A:qj6IDK7rITs"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/index?d=qj6IDK7rITs" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/index?a=9lr_bsyKZCQ:cSMDwISYc2A:yIl2AUoC8zA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/index?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"></img></a>
