		<item>
		<title>Sadly, none of the big rockets we hoped to see fly in 2020 actually will</title>
		<link>https://arstechnica.com/?p=1689608</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 13 Jul 2020 13:57:54 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Eric Berger]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Science]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://arstechnica.com/?p=1689608</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Which will fly first: NASA's SLS rocket or SpaceX's Super Heavy booster?]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id="rss-wrap">
<figure class="intro-image intro-left"><img src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/37918-800x488.jpg" alt="Artist's view of the configuration of Ariane 6 using four boosters on the ELA-4 launch pad together with its mobile gantry."><p class="caption" style="font-size:0.8em"><a href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/37918.jpg" class="enlarge-link" data-height="624" data-width="1024">Enlarge</a> <span class="sep">/</span> Artist's view of the configuration of Ariane 6 using four boosters on the ELA-4 launch pad together with its mobile gantry. (credit: ESA-D. Ducros)</p>  </figure><div><a name="page-1"></a></div>
<p>This was <em>supposed</em> to be the year of the big rocket. At one point, as many as four large, powerful boosters were slated to take flight this year. Alas, we now know for sure that none of them are going to make it.</p>
<p>Two years ago, <a href="https://arstechnica.com/science/2018/07/the-year-2020-could-see-the-unheard-of-debut-of-four-big-rockets-or-not/">Ars published an article</a> outlining the four large and powerful rockets expected to make their debuts: Arianespace's Ariane 6, NASA's Space Launch System, Blue Origin's New Glenn, and United Launch Alliance's Vulcan-Centaur. Our confidence in each of these boosters launching in 2020 ranged from medium-high for the Ariane 6 (oops!) to low for New Glenn and Vulcan-Centaur.</p>

<p>Given that none of these rockets will, in fact, debut this year, we decided to revisit the realm of heavy lift. We will also add three more contenders for a 2021 launch: Japan's H3 rocket, Northrop Grumman's Omega booster, and SpaceX's Super Heavy first stage. Here, we try to rank these seven vehicles by which will launch soonest. Please note these are estimates based upon vastly incomplete information and are almost certainly wrong.</p></div><p><a href="https://arstechnica.com/?p=1689608#p3">Read 26 remaining paragraphs</a> | <a href="https://arstechnica.com/?p=1689608&comments=1">Comments</a></p><div class="feedflare">
<a href="http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/index?a=MxbmbrNqyE0:eQ4Fmfxw8jc:V_sGLiPBpWU"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/index?i=MxbmbrNqyE0:eQ4Fmfxw8jc:V_sGLiPBpWU" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/index?a=MxbmbrNqyE0:eQ4Fmfxw8jc:F7zBnMyn0Lo"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/index?i=MxbmbrNqyE0:eQ4Fmfxw8jc:F7zBnMyn0Lo" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/index?a=MxbmbrNqyE0:eQ4Fmfxw8jc:qj6IDK7rITs"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/index?d=qj6IDK7rITs" border="0"></img></a> <a href="http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/index?a=MxbmbrNqyE0:eQ4Fmfxw8jc:yIl2AUoC8zA"><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/index?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" border="0"></img></a>
